definition.value: This is an AE which include asymptomatic infections, the primary infection, infectious mononucleosis, and the progression of asymptomatic or primary infections .
This is an AE which is an epilepsy syndrome in which new-onset refractory status epilepticus (NORSE) is preceded by febrile illness 24 hours to 2 weeks prior to the onset of seizures.
This is an AE which is a infection caused by genus of Gram-variable-staining facultative anaerobic bacteria of which Gardnerella vaginalis is the only species.
This is an AE which is an infection by a type of intestinal parasite known as a hookworm.
This is an AE which is the name given to all viruses in the genus Bocaparvovirus of virus family Parvoviridae that are known to infect humans.

This is an AE which has been associated with different epilepsy syndromes, including febrile seizures and status epilepticus, acute symptomatic seizures secondary to encephalitis and temporal lobe epilepsy.
This is an AE which is an infectious disease caused by certain types of human herpes viruses.
This is an AE which is a family of viruses whose natural hosts are primarily mammals such as human.
This is an AE which is the causation of a disease, a harmful complication, or other ill effect by any medical activity, including diagnosis, intervention, error, or negligence.
This is an AE which is the invasion of an implant site by disease-causing agents, their multiplication, and the reaction of host tissues to the infectious agents and the toxins they produce.

This is an AE which is defined as infections occurring up to 30 days after surgery (or up to one year after surgery in patients receiving implants) and affecting either the incision or deep tissue at the operation site.

This is an AE which is the passing of a pathogen causing communicable disease from an infected host individual or group to a particular individual or group, regardless of whether the other individual was previously infected such as indirect infection.
This is an AE which is a wound received from the mouth of an animal or human and can caused infection.
This is an AE which is a closed infected sac , having a distinct envelope and division compared with the nearby tissue.
This is an AE which has been widely documented in marine mammals and may cause morbidity and mortality at levels that result in population level effects.

This is an AE which is the invasion of an organism's body tissues by disease-causing agents, their multiplication, and the reaction of host tissues to the infectious agents and the toxins they produce such as  via vaccinee.
This is an AE which is an infection usually caused by the Epstein–Barr virus (EBV).
This is an AE which is the inflammation with infective of the fluid-filled sheath (called the synovium) that surrounds a tendon, typically leading to joint pain, swelling, and stiffness.

This is an AE which refers a member of polyomaviridae family, has been described as a cause of the progressive multifocal leukoencephalopathy (PML) and it is a potentially fatal, disabling demyelinating infection of the brain occurring mostly in the setting of immunosuppression.

This is an AE which is a genus of pathogenic Gram-negative bacteria that includes the species L. pneumophila, causing legionellosis (all illnesses caused by Legionella) including a pneumonia-type illness called Legionnaires' disease and a mild flu-like illness called Pontiac fever.

This is an AE which is an atypical mycobacterial infection, i.e. one with nontuberculous mycobacteria or NTM, caused by Mycobacterium avium complex (MAC), which is made of two Mycobacterium species, M. avium and M. intracellulare.
This is an AE which occur after traumatic injuries, minor skin lesions, nonpenetrating injuries, natural childbirth, and in postsurgical and immunocompromised patients.
This is an AE which is an infection caused by  large genus of bacteria that colonize the mucosal surfaces of many animals.
This is an AE which is associated with high mortality and morbidity and is transmitted by direct and indirect contact.
This is an AE which is infections of the neonate (newborn) acquired during prenatal development or in the first four weeks of life (neonatal period).
This is an AE which is inflammation with noninfective of the outermost layer of the white part of the eye and the inner surface of the eyelid.
This is an AE which is a non-destructive and noninfective disease that causes inflammation of the gums.
This is an AE which is serologically cross-reactive and cross-protective, and after the cessation of smallpox vaccination, CPXV and other OPV infections represent an emerging threat to human health.
This is an AE which is involved in both juvenile and adult laryngeal papilloma.
This is an AE which is a common cause of seasonal upper respiratory tract infections in children and adults.
This is an AE which is an important emerging infection in young infants, able to cause sepsis-like disease and meningoencephalitis, especially in newborns.
This is an AE which may cause significant fetal damage, and in rare cases, brain anomalies and neurodevelopmental insults, especially if infection occurs in the first 20 weeks of pregnancy.

This is an AE which is an infection caused by viruses have linear, single-stranded DNA (ssDNA) genomes that typically contain two genes encoding for a replication initiator protein, called NS1, and the protein the viral capsid is made of.
This is an AE which is an infection caused by species of parasitic protozoa that causes tertian malaria in humans.
This is an AE which is one of the most common causes of acute glomerulonephritis in children.
This is an AE which is the invasion of post procedural tissue by disease-causing agents, their multiplication, and the reaction of host tissues to the infectious agents and the toxins they produce.
This is an AE which is considered surgical site infection.
This is an AE which is an infection caused by a gram-positive, anaerobic, rod-shaped genus of bacteria .
This is an AE which is a genus of Gram-negative Proteobacteria caused infection.
This is an AE which is the invasion of puncture site  tissues by disease-causing agents, their multiplication, and the reaction of host tissues to the infectious agents and the toxins they produce.
This is an AE which is an infection caused by a type of virus that inserts a copy of its RNA genome into the DNA of a host cell that it invades, thus changing the genome of that cell.
This is an AE which is a leading cause of severe, dehydrating gastroenteritis in children <5 years of age.
This is an AE which is an infection caused by the  species of rod-shaped, Gram-negative bacteria in the family Yersiniaceae.

This is an AE which is a  severe invasive  infection caused by genus of gram-positive coccus (plural cocci) or spherical bacteria that belongs to the family Streptococcaceae, within the order Lactobacillales (lactic acid bacteria), in the phylum Firmicutes.
This is an AE which is an infection caused by a  strictly aerobic Gram-negative bacterium that has a single polar flagellum with slow motility.

This is an AE which is an infection caused by that contains distinctive diderm (double-membrane) gram-negative bacteria, most of which have long, helically coiled (corkscrew-shaped or spiraled) cells.
This is an AE which is an infection caused by a  genus of Gram-negative bacteria,comprising at least ten species.

This is an AE which is an infection caused by a genus of gram-positive coccus (plural cocci) or spherical bacteria that belongs to the family Streptococcaceae, within the order Lactobacillales (lactic acid bacteria), in the phylum Firmicutes.
This is an AE which is an infection caused by  small tubular structures of the skin that produce sweat.
